'''Cannabis in Belgium''' is illegal, but personal possession has been decriminalized since 2003;<ref name="Mistral2013">{{cite book|author=Willm Mistral|title=Emerging Perspectives on Substance Misuse|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXktdzjvKdgC&pg=PT21|date=27 June 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-30662-8|pages=21–}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emcdda.europa.eu/html.cfm/index5174EN.html?pluginMethod=eldd.countryprofiles&country=BE |title=EMCDDA &#124; Country Profile - Belgium |publisher=Emcdda.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2016-12-06}}</ref> adults over the age of 18 are allowed to possess up to 3 grams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polfed-fedpol.be/|title=Federale politie - Police fdrale|author=Police fdrale - CGPR Webteam|publisher=|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url = http://www.erowid.org/plants/cannabis/cannabis_law.shtml#belgium |title = Cannabis legal status vault – Belgium |publisher = Erowid.org |date =  |accessdate = 2011-02-17 }}</ref>

In June 2015, [[Maggie De Block]] signed a royal decree legalizing certain uses of medical cannabis, which as of 2015 only include [[Sativex]] oral spray for [[multiple sclerosis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flanderstoday.eu/innovation/medical-cannabis-plantation-offers-patients-new-perspectives|title=Medical cannabis plantation offers patients new perspectives - Flanders Today|website=www.flanderstoday.eu}}</ref>

