[[Category:General medical journals]]

A '''regimen''' is a plan, a regulated course such as a [[Diet (nutrition)|diet]], [[exercise]] or [[medical treatment]], designed to give a positive result.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regimen|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/regimen }}</ref> A [[salt#Health effects|low-salt]] diet is a regimen. A course of [[penicillin]] is a regimen, and there are many [[chemotherapy regimen]]s in the treatment of [[cancer]].
== History == The work, ''Regimen in Acute Diseases'', attributed to the ancient Greek physician, [[Hippocrates of Cos]], describes the types and usage of medical regimens in his era (400 BCE). This is perhaps the first appearance of the [[terminology|term]].<ref>Hippocrates of Cos. ''On Regimen in Acute Diseases'' Francis Adams, trans. 400 BCE.</ref><ref>Riley, Mark T, "Hippocrates", Great Thinkers of the Western World, HarperCollins Publishers, 1992. 16</ref> [[PubMed]] at the [[US National Library of Medicine]] lists over 220,000 articles using the term "regimen" from 1892 to January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=regimen |title=regimen - PubMed|author=pubmeddev|work=nih.gov|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> In the context of medieval medicine, regimen referred to the careful management of habits, diet, and schedule to keep the four [[Humorism|humors]] in equilibrium. By manipulating the six non-naturals (airs, diet, sleep, exercise, evacuation, and emotion) a person could keep track of their physical and mental wellbeing by attending to regimen.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yaguchi|first=N.|year=2010|title=Non-Naturals in Islamic Medicine|url=|journal=Journal of Japanese History of Medicine|volume=56|pages=53–66}}</ref>
==Usage in statistics== In economic statistics, a regimen refers to the selected goods and/or services priced for the purpose of compiling a [[price index]]. The most well known example is the [[consumer price index]].
